'''Syed Rizwan Farook''' (June 14, 1987<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2015/12/04/killer-in-california-rampage-seemed-pious-and-peaceful-then-snapped-motive-still-unknown.html |title=FBI: Investigating Calif massacre as 'act of terrorism' |publisher=CNBC |date=December 4, 2015 |accessdate=December 8, 2015}}</ref>{{snds}}December 2, 2015) and '''Tashfeen Malik'''{{efn|name=malikurdu|Tashfeen Malik ({{lang-ur |{{Script/Nastaliq|تاشفين ملک}}}} / {{IPA-hns|tɑːʃfiːn məlɪk}})}} (July 13, 1986<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/12/06/us/san-bernardino-shooter-tashfeen-malik/?iid=ob_article_footer_expansion&iref=obinsite |title=Tashfeen Malik, the San Bernardino shooter: Who was she? |first1=Pat |last1=St. Claire |first2=Greg |last2=Botelho |first3=Ralph |last3=Ellis |date=December 6, 2015 |accessdate=December 8, 2015 |publisher=CNN}}</ref>{{snds}}December 2, 2015) were the two perpetrators of [[2015 San Bernardino attack|a terrorist attack]] at the [[Inland Regional Center]] in [[San Bernardino, California|San Bernardino]], [[California]], on December 2, 2015. In the attack, they killed 14 people and injured 22 others.<ref name="pe">{{cite news |title=San Bernardino Shooting: 22nd injured victim steps forward, FBI says |agency=The Press Enterprise |date=December 10, 2015 |accessdate=December 10, 2015 |url=http://www.pe.com/articles/san-788876-shooting-bernardino.html}}</ref><ref name="cnbc">{{cite web|last1=Rosenfeld|first1=Everette|title=Upwards of 14 people dead in San Bernardino mass shooting: Police department chief|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2015/12/02/authorities-responding-to-reports-of-mass-shooting-in-san-bernardino-california-nbc-los-angeles.html|publisher=CNBC|accessdate=December 2, 2015}}</ref><ref name="AP">{{cite news|last1=Myers|first1=Amanda|title=14 dead, more than a dozen wounded in California shooting|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/e5660a0b4ae1436fb2c51354cef8f6db/california-police-respond-report-active-shooter|work=Associated Press|accessdate=December 2, 2015}}</ref> Both died in a [[shootout]] with police later that same day.<ref name="ABC" /><ref name="Suspects">{{cite web |date=December 3, 2015 |url=http://abc7.com/news/2-suspects-in-san-bernardino-mass-shooting-identified/1107640/ |title=Suspects in San Bernardino mass shooting identified as Syed Farook and Tashfeen Malik |publisher=ABC7 |accessdate=December 3, 2015}}</ref><ref name=CNN.Hero>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/02/12/us/beyond-the-call-of-duty-andy-capps/|title=Gunfire, a text and a tear: A hero behind the San Bernardino shootout|work=CNN|date=February 12, 2016|accessdate=February 12, 2016|first=Kyung|last=Lah|first2=Jason|last2=Kravarik}}</ref>
== Backgrounds ==
=== Rizwan Farook === Farook was born in [[Chicago, Illinois]],<ref name=TurkewitzBorn>{{cite news|last1=Turkewitz|first1=Julie|last2=Mueller|first2=Benjamin|title=Couple Kept Tight Lid on Plans for San Bernardino Shooting|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/04/us/san-bernardino-shooting-syed-rizwan-farook.html|accessdate=December 3, 2015|work=The New York Times|date=December 3, 2015}}</ref><ref name="LeftBabyDaughter" /><ref name="BloodTuckerAP">{{cite news|last1=Blood|first1=Michael R.|last2=Tucker|first2=Eric|title=Records: Suspect in deadly shooting had troubled upbringing|agency=Associated Press|url=https://news.yahoo.com/records-suspect-deadly-shooting-had-troubled-upbringing-205951950.html|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=December 4, 2015|accessdate=December 4, 2015}}</ref> and was a U.S. citizen at the time of the attack. His parents had immigrated from Pakistan.<ref name="CluesMotive" />
==== Personal life ==== According to sources, Farook had a "troubled childhood"<ref>{{cite news|title=San Bernardino Suspect Syed Farook's Troubled Childhood: Father Was Alcoholic, Mother Alleged Domestic Abuse In Court Papers|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/san-bernardino-suspect-syed-farooks-troubled-childhood-father-was-alcoholic-mother-2210359|newspaper=International Business Times|date=December 3, 2015|first=Julia|last=Glum}}</ref> and grew up in an "abusive" home in which his father was often violent towards his mother.<ref>{{cite news|title=San Bernardino shooter Syed Farook grew up in abusive home and witnessed father attack mother: court records|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/syed-farook-allah-fearing-man-snowboarding-article-1.2453836|work=Daily News|location=New York|date=December 3, 2015|first=Larry|last=McShane}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Matt |last=Hamilton |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-san-bernardino-shooter-endured-turbulent-home-life-according-to-court-documents-20151203-story.html|title=San Bernardino shooting suspect endured turbulent home life, according to court documents |work=Los Angeles Times |date=December 2, 2015 |accessdate=December 4, 2015}}</ref><ref name=SernaParviniHamiltonKnoll>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-san-bernardino-attack-life-insurance-lawsuit-20160531-snap-story.html|title=Should a terrorist's family collect insurance money after he killed 14 people in the San Bernardino attack?|work=The Los Angeles Times|date=May 31, 2016|accessdate=June 1, 2016|first=Joseph|last=Serna|first2=Sarah|last2=Parvini|first3=Matt|last3=Hamilton|first4=Corina|last4=Knoll}}</ref> Farook grew up in [[Riverside, California]], and attended [[La Sierra High School]], graduating in 2004, one year early.<ref name="OCRegister">{{cite news |url=http://www.ocregister.com/articles/farook-694704-san-bernardino.html |title=What is known so far about Syed Farook and Tashfeen Malik, the San Bernardino shooting suspects |newspaper=Orange County Register|date=December 3, 2015}}</ref><ref name="O'Neill">{{cite news |first=Patrick |last=O'Neill |url=http://www.pe.com/articles/san-788171-bernardino-graduate.html |title=San Bernardino Shooting: Suspect graduated CSUSB |newspaper=The Press-Enterprise |date=December 3, 2015}}</ref> He attended [[California State University, San Bernardino]], and received a [[bachelor's degree]] in [[environmental health]] in either 2009 or 2010.<ref name="OCRegister" /><ref name="O'Neill" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/12/03/they-were-a-couple-the-striking-difference-between-the-san-bernardino-suspects-and-other-mass-shooters/|title=Authorities pick through suspects' path: Marriage, baby and then bloodshed|first=Yanan|last=Wang|date=December 3, 2015|work=The Washington Post}}</ref> He was a student for one semester in 2014 at [[California State University, Fullerton]] in their graduate program for [[environmental engineering]], but never completed the program.<ref name="OCRegister" />
Farook had a profile on the [[online dating|dating website]] iMilap.com, in which he listed backyard [[target practice]] as a hobby. A lawyer for Farook's family also said that he would go to [[firing range]]s by himself.<ref>{{cite news|title=Who were Syed Rizwan Farook and Tashfeen Malik?|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/12/03/us/syed-farook-tashfeen-malik-mass-shooting-profile/|publisher=CNN|date=December 3, 2015|accessdate=December 7, 2015}}</ref>
Farook worked as a [[food safety|food inspector]] for the San Bernardino County Department of Public Health for five years before the shooting.<ref>{{cite web|title=San Bernardino Shooting: Two Suspects Dead After Gun Battle|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/active-shooter-reported-in-southern-california-1449085770|work=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=December 3, 2015}}</ref><ref name="auto">{{cite web|title=San Bernardino shooting live updates: Syed Farook named as a suspect in attack that killed 14|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-san-bernardino-shooting-live-updates-htmlstory.html|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=December 3, 2015}}</ref><ref name="CNNwhatweknow" /> From July to December 2010, he was a seasonal employee for the county. He was hired as an [[Environmental health officer|environmental health specialist]] trainee on January 28, 2012, and became a permanent employee on February 8, 2014.<ref name="OCRegister" /> Coworkers described Farook as quiet and polite, and said that he held no obvious grudges.<ref name="LATIMES-Americandream" /> Two weeks before the attack, he reportedly tried to explain, during an office conversation, that [[Religion of Peace|Islam was a peaceful religion]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/foreigners/2015/12/syed_farook_and_tashfeen_malik_may_have_been_inspired_to_kill_what_it_means.html|title=At War With an Idea: What if the freedom to bear arms is also the freedom to be a jihadi?|first=William|last=Saletan|author-link=William Saletan|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |date=December 4, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-san-bernardino-shooter-victim-islam-20151204-story.html|title=San Bernardino victim was upfront about politics and religion – with Farook too|first=Veronica|last=Rocha|work=Los Angeles Times|date=December 4, 2015}}</ref>
====Religious views and travels==== According to family members and coworkers, Farook was a devout [[Sunni Muslim]], and traveled to Saudi Arabia several times, including to complete the [[hajj]]<!--Do not capitalize; it's a common noun rather than a proper noun--> in 2013.<ref name="CluesMotive"/><ref name="CNNRadicalized"/> Farook attended prayers at the [[Islamic Center of Riverside]] twice a day, in the mornings and the evenings, according to an interview in ''[[The New York Times]]'' with Mustafa H. Kuko, the Center's director. According to the ''Times'', Farook stood out as especially devout and "kept a bit of a distance" from other congregants.<ref name=Nagourney>{{cite news|last1=Nagourney|first1=Adam|title=Couple Kept Tight Lid on Plans for San Bernardino Shooting|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/04/us/san-bernardino-shooting-syed-rizwan-farook.html|accessdate=December 4, 2015|work=The New York Times|date=December 3, 2015}}</ref> During that time, according to friends, he never discussed politics. Farook abruptly stopped going to the mosque in 2014 following his marriage.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Thomas|first1=Dexter|title=San Bernardino shooting suspect stopped attending mosque two years ago|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-san-bernardino-shooting-suspect-serious-about-studying-the-koran-20151203-story.html|accessdate=December 13, 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|date=December 3, 2015}}</ref>
The Italian newspaper ''[[La Stampa]]'' reported that Farook's father said that his son "shared the ideology of [[Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi|Al Baghdadi]] to create an Islamic state" and that he was fixated with [[Israel]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/san-bernardino-suspect-was-obsessed-with-israel-father-says/ |title=San Bernardino suspect was obsessed with Israel, father says|publisher=CBS News|accessdate=December 21, 2015}}</ref> A spokesperson for the [[Council on American–Islamic Relations]] (CAIR) later claimed the father did not recall making these statements about his son.<ref>{{cite web|title=San Bernardino attacker was 'normal guy' while practicing at shooting range|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-san-bernardino-shootings-fbi-raid-20151207-story.html|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=December 8, 2015}}</ref>
=== Tashfeen Malik === Malik was born in [[Pakistan]] but lived most of her life in Saudi Arabia.<ref name="TurkewitzBorn" /><ref name="auto" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-california-shooting-pakistan-idUSKBN0TN1YX20151204|first=Mehreen|last=Zahra-Malik|title=Exclusive: Investigators piece together portrait of Pakistani woman in shooting massacre|agency=Reuters|date=December 4, 2015|accessdate=December 4, 2015}}</ref> Her original hometown was [[Karor Lal Esan]], {{convert|450|km|mi}} southwest of [[Islamabad]], Pakistan.<ref name="Tashfeen hometown">{{cite web|title=Family members say Tashfeen Malik became more religious in years prior to massacre|url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2015/12/06/family-members-say-tashfeen-malik-became-more-religious-in-years-prior-to/?intcmp=hpbt1|publisher=Fox News Channel|accessdate=December 6, 2015}}</ref> Her landowning family was described as politically influential in the town.<ref name="AttendedIslamicInstitute">{{cite news|first=Aoun|last=Sahi|title=San Bernardino assailant attended Islamic institute in Pakistan |url=http://www.latimes.com/world/afghanistan-pakistan/la-fg-pakistan-san-bernardino-20151206-story.html|work=Los Angeles Times|date=December 6, 2015|accessdate=December 13, 2015}}</ref>
==== Studies in Multan ==== Malik returned to Pakistan to study [[pharmacology]] at [[Bahauddin Zakariya University]] in [[Multan]], beginning the program in 2007 and graduating in 2012.<ref name="inspired">{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2015/12/04/suspects-family-shocked-killings/76773382/|title=FBI: No evidence San Bernardino killers were part of a cell|work=USA Today|date=December 4, 2015|accessdate=December 4, 2015}}</ref><ref name="AttendedIslamicInstitute" /><ref name="NYT Al-Huda">{{cite news|first1=Salman |last1=Masood |first2=Declan |last2=Walsh|title=Tashfeen Malik Attended Conservative Religious School in Pakistan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/08/world/asia/tashfeen-malik-attended-conservative-religious-school-in-pakistan.html|work=The New York Times|date=December 7, 2015}}</ref> [[Ministry of Interior (Saudi Arabia)|Saudi Interior Ministry]] spokesman Major General Mansour Al-Turki denied reports that Malik grew up in his country, saying that she only visited Saudi Arabia for a few weeks in 2008 and again in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Aunt: San Bernardino suspect 'became more devout'|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2015/12/06/san-bernardino-shooting/76879058/|work=USA Today|date=December 6, 2015|accessdate=December 11, 2015|first=Jane|last=Onyanga-Omara|first2=John|last2=Bacon}}</ref> The city of Multan has been linked to [[Jihadism|jihadist]] activity.<ref name="USATodaySchool">{{cite web|title=Female San Bernardino suspect went to religious school|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2015/12/07/san-bernardino-suspect-religious-shool/76911152/|work=USA Today|date=December 7, 2015|accessdate=December 7, 2015}}</ref>
While in Multan, Malik attended the local center of the [[Al-Huda Institute|Al-Huda International Seminary]], a women-only [[madrassa|religious academy]] network with seminaries across Pakistan and branches in the U.S. and Canada that was founded in 1994.<ref name="NYT Al-Huda" /><ref name="USATodaySchool" /><ref name="TimCraig">{{cite news|last1=Craig|first1=Tim|title=Pakistan is focus in hunt|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/pakistan-is-focus-in-hunt-for-clues-to-california-shooters-radical-turn/2015/12/09/aaec9a14-9ad3-11e5-aca6-1ae3be6f06d2_story.html|accessdate=December 11, 2015|work=The Washington Post|date=December 9, 2015}}</ref> The school is aligned with the [[Wahhabi]] form of Sunni Islam.<ref name="TimCraig" /> According to school records, Malik enrolled in an eighteen-month [[Quran]]ic studies course with Al-Huda on April 17, 2013, and left on May 3, 2014, telling administrators that she was leaving to get married. Malik expressed an interest in completing the [[Distance education|course by correspondence]], but never did so.<ref name="NYT Al-Huda" />
According to experts, Al-Huda "draws much of its support from women from educated, relatively affluent backgrounds."<ref name="NYT Al-Huda" /> Faiza Mushtaq, a Pakistani scholar that studied the organization, said that "these Al-Huda classes is teaching these urban, educated, upper-middle-class women a very conservative interpretation of Islam that makes them very judgmental about others around them." According to the ''Los Angeles Times'', Al-Huda seminaries promote anti-Western views and hard-line practices in a fashion that "could encourage some adherents to lash out against non-believers."<ref name=LATimes.Al-Huda>{{cite web |first1=Aoun |last1=Sahi |first2=Shashank |last2=Bengali |title=School that taught San Bernardino assailant is known for anti-Western, fundamentalist views |url=http://www.latimes.com/world/asia/la-fg-school-san-bernardino-fundamentalist-20151207-story.html |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=December 7, 2015}}</ref> The ''New York Times'' reported that the institute "teaches a strict literalist interpretation of the Quran, although it does not advocate violent jihad."<ref name="MissedSocialMedia">{{cite news|first=Matt|last=Apuzzo|first2=Michael S.|last2=Schmidt|first3=Julia|last3=Preston|title=U.S. Visa Process Missed San Bernardino Wife's Zealotry on Social Media|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/13/us/san-bernardino-attacks-us-visa-process-tashfeen-maliks-remarks-on-social-media-about-jihad-were-missed.html|work=The New York Times|date=December 13, 2015}}</ref> An Al-Huda administrator from the head office in Islamabad said that terrorism "is against the teachings of Islam" and that the school's curriculum did not endorse violence.<ref name=LATimes.Al-Huda />
==== Marriage and entry into United States ==== According to one of Farook's coworkers, Malik and her husband married about a month after he traveled to Saudi Arabia in early 2014; the two had met over the Internet.<ref name="Suspects" /><ref name="LATIMES-Americandream">{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-syed-farook-had-traveled-to-saudi-arabia-married-appeared-to-live-american-dream-co-workers-say-20151202-story.html|title=San Bernardino shooting suspect traveled to Saudi Arabia, was married, appeared to be living 'American Dream,' co-workers say|work=Los Angeles Times|date=December 2, 2015}}</ref> Malik joined Farook in California shortly after their wedding. A U.S. marriage certificate reported their marriage in Riverside on August 16, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2015/12/04/investigators-probe-whether-wife-radicalized-husband-before-san-bernardino/|title=Investigators probe whether wife radicalized husband before San Bernardino massacre|publisher=Fox News Channel|date=December 4, 2015|accessdate=December 8, 2015}}</ref> At the time of her death, Malik and Farook had a six-month-old daughter.<ref name="CNNwhatweknow">{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/12/03/us/what-we-know-san-bernardino-mass-shooting/index.html|title=Mass shooting at Inland Regional Center: What we know|last=Ahmed|first=Saaed|date=December 3, 2015|publisher=CNN|accessdate=December 3, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nation.com.pk/international/03-Dec-2015/san-bernardino-shooting-cair-claims-female-assailant-was-from-pakistan|title=California shooting: CAIR claims female assailant was from Pakistan|date=December 3, 2015|work=The Nation|accessdate=December 3, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1223982|title=California killing: Female assailant was from Pakistan, CAIR claims|agency=Reuters|accessdate=December 3, 2015}}</ref>
Malik entered the United States on a [[K-1 visa|K-1 (fiancée) visa]] with a [[Pakistani passport]].<ref name="CluesMotive" /><ref name="CNNRadicalized" /><ref name="Preston">{{cite news |first=Julia |last=Preston |url=https://www.nytimes.com/live/san-bernardino-shooting/from-fiance-visa-to-green-card |title=From Fiancé Visa to Green Card |newspaper=The New York Times |date=December 3, 2015}}</ref> According to a State Department spokesman, all applicants for such visas are fully screened.<ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. authorities look for militant links to shooters in California mass slaying|url=http://in.reuters.com/article/2015/12/03/california-shooting-idINKBN0TM0SO20151203|agency=Reuters|accessdate=December 3, 2015}}</ref> Malik's application for [[Permanent residence (United States)|permanent residency]] (a "green card") was completed by Farook on her behalf in September 2014, and she was granted a conditional green card in July 2015.<ref name="Preston" /> Obtaining such a green card would have required the couple to prove that the marriage was legitimate.<ref name="CluesMotive" /><ref name="Preston" /> As is standard practice,<ref name="CluesMotive" /><ref name="Preston" /> as part of her visa application with the State Department and application for a green card, Malik submitted her fingerprints and underwent "three extensive national security and criminal background screenings" using Homeland Security and State Department databases. Malik also underwent two in-person interviews, the first with a consular officer in Pakistan and the second with an immigration officer in the U.S. after applying for a green card.<ref name="MissedSocialMedia" /> No irregularities or signs of suspicion were found in the record of Malik's interview with the Pakistani consular officer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pe.com/articles/malik-791107-tashfeen-visa.html|title=SAN BERNARDINO SHOOTING: No irregularities in Malik visa interview, report says|work=The Press-Enterprise|date=January 7, 2016|accessdate=January 7, 2016|first=Richard K.|last=De Atley}}</ref>
Malik reportedly had become very religious in the years before the attack, wearing both the [[niqab]] and [[burqa]] while urging others to do so as well.<ref>{{cite news |first1=Michael R. |last1=Blood |first2=Tami |last2=Abdollah |url=http://www.kaaltv.com/article/stories/s3982781.shtml |title=Who Was Tashfeen Malik? |publisher=KAAL |agency=Associated Press |date=December 5, 2015}}</ref><ref name="Bruton">{{cite news |first=F. Brinley |last=Bruton |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/san-bernardino-shooting/tashfeen-malik-mom-california-rampage-became-very-devout-report-n475031 |title=Tashfeen Malik, Mom in California Rampage, Became Very Devout: Report |publisher=NBC News |date=December 6, 2015}}</ref> Pakistani media reported that Malik had ties to the radical [[Red Mosque]] in [[Islamabad]], but a cleric and a spokesman from the mosque vehemently denied these claims, saying that they had never heard of Malik before the shooting.<ref name="Bruton" /><ref name="ReutersMalikRadicalization">{{cite news|title=Pakistani in California shooting became hardline in S. Arabia&nbsp;— relatives|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/california-shooting-pakistan-idUSKBN0TO0MB20151206|agency=Reuters|accessdate=December 6, 2015}}</ref> Malik's estranged relatives say that she had left the [[Liberal Muslim movements|moderate Islam]] of her family and had become [[Radicalization|radicalized]] while living in Saudi Arabia.<ref name="ReutersMalikRadicalization" /><ref>{{cite news |agency=Associated Press |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/isis-san-bernardino-shooting-1.3352268 |title=San Bernardino shooter Tashfeen Malik grew hardline in Saudi Arabia, family says |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |date=December 6, 2015}}</ref> Saudi Interior Ministry spokesman Al-Turki rejected this claim, stating that Saudi officials received no indication that Malik was radicalized while living there.<ref>{{cite news |work=Associated Press |url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/3c3ed22323854a9b922e6036375255a7/latest-saudi-spokesman-says-no-sign-radicalization|title=The Latest: Muslims at memorial service express grief, fear |date=December 6, 2015}}</ref>
=== Internet activities === On December 16, 2015, FBI Director James Comey said, "We can see from our investigation that in late 2013, before there is a physical meeting of these two people [Farook and Malik] resulting in their engagement and then journey to the United States, they are communicating online, showing signs in that communication of their joint commitment to jihadism and to martyrdom. Those communications are direct, private messages."<ref name="BakerSantora">{{cite news |first1=Al |last1=Baker |first2=Marc |last2=Santora |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/17/us/san-bernardino-attackers-discussed-jihad-in-private-messages-fbi-says.html |title=San Bernardino Attackers Discussed Jihad in Private Messages, F.B.I. Says |newspaper=The New York Times |date=December 16, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Paul |last=Lewis |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/dec/16/san-bernardino-attackers-jihad-social-media-fbi |title=San Bernardino attackers did not post about jihad on social media, FBI says |newspaper=The Guardian |date=December 16, 2015}}</ref>
Early reports had erroneously stated that Malik had openly expressed jihadist beliefs on social media, leading to calls for U.S. immigration officials to routinely review social media as part of background checks, which is not part of the current procedure.<ref name="MissedSocialMedia" /> Comey subsequently clarified that the remarks were "direct private messages" that were not publicly accessible and that "So far, in this investigation, we have found no evidence of posting on social media."<ref name="BakerSantora" />
Comey said that the FBI's investigation had revealed that Farook and Malik were "consuming poison on the Internet" and both had become radicalized "before they started courting or dating each other online" and "before the emergence of ISIL."<ref name="BakerSantora" /><ref>{{cite news|first1=Michael |last1=Martinez |first2=Catherine E. |last2=Shoichet |first3=Pamela |last3=Brown|title=San Bernardino shooting: Couple radicalized before they met, FBI says|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/12/09/us/san-bernardino-shooting/index.html|publisher=CNN|date=December 9, 2015}}</ref> As a result, Comey said that "untangling the motivations of which particular terrorist [[propaganda]] motivated in what way remains a challenge in these investigations, and our work is ongoing there."<ref name="BakerSantora" />
== Planning of the attack == In [[Senate Judiciary Committee]] testimony given on December 9, 2015, FBI Director [[James B. Comey]] said that the FBI investigation has shown that Farook and Malik were "homegrown violent extremists" who were "inspired by [[foreign terrorist organization]]s." Comey also said that Farook and Malik "were talking to each other about [[jihad]] and martyrdom," before their engagement and as early as the end of 2013.<ref name="WilliamsAbdullah">{{cite news|first1=Pete|last1=Williams|first2=Halimah|last2=Abdullah|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/san-bernardino-shooting/fbi-san-bernardino-shooters-radicalized-they-met-n476971|title=FBI: San Bernardino Shooters Radicalized Before They Met|publisher=NBC News|date=December 9, 2015}}</ref><ref name="WaPo.jihad">{{cite web|last1=Goldman|first1=Adam|last2=Berman|first2=Mark|title=San Bernardino Attackers Talked 'About Jihad and Martyrdom' in 2013|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-nation/wp/2015/12/09/san-bernardino-attackers-talked-about-jihad-and-martyrdom-in-2013|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref> They reportedly spent at least a year preparing for the attack, including taking target practice and making plans to take care of their child and Farook's mother.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Andrew|last1=Blankstein|first2=Robert|last2=Windrem|first3=Pete|last3=Williams|first4=Richard|last4=Esposito|first5=Hannah|last5=Rappleye|title=San Bernardino Shooters Practiced for Attack a Year in Advance|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/san-bernardino-shooting/san-bernardino-shooters-planned-attack-least-year-advance-n476521|publisher=NBC News|date=December 8, 2015|accessdate=December 8, 2015}}</ref> Comey has said that although the investigation has shown that Farook and Malik were radicalized and possibly inspired by foreign terrorist organizations, there is no indication that the couple were directed by such a group or part of a broader [[terrorist cell|cell or network]].<ref name="inspired" /><ref name="USAT.Comey">{{cite web|title=ISIL radio: Two supporters carried out San Bernardino massacre|first=Gregg|last=Zoroya|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation-now/2015/12/05/isil-radio-two-supporters-carried-out-san-bernardino-massacre/76828170|work=USA Today|accessdate=December 5, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2015/12/04/suspects-family-shocked-killings/76773382|title=FBI: No evidence San Bernardino killers were part of a cell|date=December 4, 2015|work=USA Today}}</ref>
The FBI has said that there were "telephonic connections" between the couple and other people of interest in FBI probes.<ref>{{cite news |date=December 4, 2015|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-35006404|title=San Bernardino shootings investigated as terrorism – FBI|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> Comey said that the case did not follow the typical pattern for mass shootings or terrorist attacks.<ref name="inspired"/> A senior U.S. law enforcement official said that Farook contacted "persons of interest" who were possibly tied to terrorism, although these contacts were not "substantial."<ref name="WP-ties">{{cite news|last1=Ryan|first1=Missy|last2=Berman|first2=Mark|last3=Achenbach|first3=Joel|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-nation/wp/2015/12/03/fbi-takes-over-san-bernardino-investigation-as-authorities-seek-motive-for-attack-that-killed-14-people|title=Arsenal of explosives, ammunition found at home of San Bernardino attackers as FBI seeks motive|date=December 3, 2015|accessdate=December 4, 2015|work=The Washington Post}}</ref> A senior federal official said that Farook had some contact with people from the [[al-Nusra Front|Nusra Front]], the official [[al-Qaeda]] affiliate in [[Syria]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/News/12392/21/Gulf-allies-and-%E2%80%98Army-of-Conquest%E2%80%99.aspx|title=Gulf allies and 'Army of Conquest|newspaper=[[Al-Ahram Weekly]]|date=May 28, 2015|accessdate=December 11, 2015}}</ref> and [[Al-Shabaab (militant group)|Shabaab]] of Somalia, but specifics were unclear.<ref name="inspired" /><ref name="Reuters-ISIS">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-california-shooting-isis-idUSKBN0TN1SR20151204|title=FBI investigating California massacre as 'act of terrorism'|agency=Reuters |accessdate=December 4, 2015|date=December 4, 2015}}</ref><ref name="LATimesProbedAsTerror">{{cite news|first1=Richard A.|last1=Serrano|first2=Brian|last2=Bennett|first3=Jack|last3=Dolan|first4=Soumya|last4=Karlamangla|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-san-bernardino-shooting-isis-20151204-story.html|title=San Bernardino massacre probed as terrorism, FBI says|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=December 4, 2015}}</ref>
=== Weapons === [[File:Guns used in San-Bernardino shooting.jpg|thumb|The four guns used by the shooters. {{small|Released by the [[San Bernardino County Sheriff's Department]].}}]]
Farook and Malik used two [[.223 Remington|.223]]-caliber [[semi-automatic rifle]]s, two [[9 mm caliber]] [[semi-automatic pistol]]s, and an explosive device in the attack.<ref name="BATFWeapons" /><ref name="WSJWeapons" /><ref name="CluesMotive">{{cite news|title=San Bernardino Suspects Left Trail of Clues, but No Clear Motive|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/04/us/san-bernardino-shooting.html|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=December 3, 2015|first1=Jennifer |last1=Medina|first2=Richard |last2=Pérez-Peña|first3=Michael S. |last3=Schmidt|first4=Laurie |last4=Goodstein|date=December 3, 2015}}</ref> The rifles used were [[Ar-15 variants|variants of the AR-15]]: one was a [[DPMS Panther Arms]] A15, the other was a [[Smith & Wesson M&P15]].<ref name="CluesMotive" /><ref name="APSanBernardino">{{cite news |agency=Associated Press |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/latest-guns-california-shooting-bought-legally-35549913 |title=The Latest: Justice Department Offers Help in Shooting Probe |publisher=ABC News |date=December 3, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151203133114/http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/latest-guns-california-shooting-bought-legally-35549913|archivedate=December 3, 2015}}</ref>
The two rifles were purchased by [[2015 San Bernardino attack#Enrique Marquez Jr.|Enrique Marquez Jr.]],<ref name="MarquezComplaint">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2015/12/17/us/document-SB-Shooting-Marquez-COMPLAINT.html|title=Criminal complaint in ''United States of America v. Enrique Marquez, Jr.'', 5:15-mj-498|agency=[[United States District Court for the Central District of California]]|date=December 17, 2015}}</ref><ref name="USDOJ">{{cite press release |url=http://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/california-man-charged-conspiring-provide-material-support-terrorism-and-being-straw |title=California Man Charged with Conspiring to Provide Material Support to Terrorism and Being 'Straw Purchaser' of Assault Rifles Ultimately Used in San Bernardino, California, Attack |publisher=US Department of Justice |date=December 17, 2015}}</ref> a next-door neighbor of Farook's until May 2015<ref name=SerranoChargedWith>{{cite news|last1=Serrano|first1=Richard|title=San Bernardino shooter's friend Enrique Marquez charged with aiding plot|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-san-bernardino-marquez-20151217-story.html|accessdate=December 17, 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|date=December 17, 2015}}</ref> who is related to him by marriage.<ref name="MarquezDeepTies">{{cite news |first1=Kate |last1=Mather |first2=Matt |last2=Hamilton |first3=Richard A. |last3=Serrano |first4=Jack |last4=Dolan |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-sb-marquez-20151210-story.html|title=Enrique Marquez, who bought rifles used in San Bernardino attack, had deep ties to gunman|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=December 10, 2015}}</ref> After their purchases, the rifles were illegally transferred to Farook. The two pistols were legally purchased by Farook from [[Federal Firearms License|federally licensed firearms dealers]] in [[Corona, California]] in 2011 and 2012.<ref name="WaPoPurchase" /><ref name="FroschElinsonPalazzolo">{{cite news |first1=Dan |last1=Frosch |first2=Zusha |last2=Elinson |first3=Joe |last3=Palazzolo |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/suspected-shooter-in-san-bernardino-massacre-made-purchase-from-kentucky-arms-store-1449343406 |title=FBI Searches Home of Man Linked to Guns Used in San Bernardino Shooting |newspaper=The Wall Street Journal |date=December 5, 2015}}</ref><ref name="HauserWhatWeKnowDec4">{{cite news |first=Christine |last=Hauser |url=https://www.nytimes.com/live/san-bernardino-shooting/the-investigation-so-far/ |title=The Investigation So Far: What We Know, What We Do Not Know |newspaper=The New York Times |date=December 4, 2015}}</ref> One of the handguns was manufactured by [[Llama firearms|Llama]] and the other is a [[HS2000|Springfield XD]].<ref name="WSJWeapons" />
[[File:Tactical belt used by San Bernardino shooter.jpg|thumb|Tactical belt used by one of the shooters. {{small|Released by the [[San Bernardino County Sheriff's Department]].}}]]
The couple altered the guns: there was a failed attempt to modify the Smith & Wesson rifle to fire in [[Automatic rifle|fully automatic]] mode, they made a modification that defeated the ban on detachable [[Magazine (firearms)|magazines]], and they used a detachable [[high-capacity magazine]]. California laws limit magazines to a maximum of ten rounds, and the magazine must be fixed by a recessed button mechanism to the rifle and require [[bullet button|a tool such as a bullet, pen, or other implement]] to remove it, thereby creating a delay in the rate at which spent magazines can be replaced.<ref name="WSJWeapons" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/california-gun-laws-san-bernardino_56606dd8e4b079b2818d7034 |title=Why California's Strict Gun Laws Didn't Matter In San Bernardino | work=The Huffington Post|date=December 3, 2015}}</ref> According to the [[Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives]], the modifications made the guns illegal [[assault weapon]]s.<ref name="CluesMotive" /> The couple also [[Jungle style (firearm magazines)|taped magazines together]] to make switching them out easier. They had a total of 2,363 rounds (1,879 for the rifles and 484 for the handguns) with them at the time of the shootout.<ref name=CalmtoChaos>{{cite web|url=http://ric-zai-inc.com/Publications/cops-w0808-pub|title=Bringing Calm to Chaos|work=Police Foundation|date=September 9, 2016|accessdate=September 9, 2016}}</ref>
The explosive device left at the Inland Regional Center comprised three explosive devices connected to one another. It was contained inside the backpack left by Farook during the departmental event. The devices were described as [[pipe bomb]]s constructed with [[Christmas lights]] and tied together, combined with a [[remote controlled car]] that was switched on. The poorly constructed devices failed to explode.<ref name="LeftBabyDaughter">{{cite web|title = Suspects in California Massacre Could Have Terror Links|url = http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/san-bernardino-shooting/san-bernadino-shooting-suspects-left-baby-daughter-grandma-n473261|publisher = NBC News|accessdate = December 4, 2015}}</ref><ref name=Newsday01>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsday.com/news/nation/san-bernardino-shooting-aftermath-bomb-was-poorly-built-law-enforcement-sources-tell-ap-1.11388607|title=AP sources: Bomb in San Bernardino attack was poorly built|publisher=Newsday|agency=Associated Press|date=January 25, 2016|accessdate=January 25, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Melissa |last=Chan |url=http://time.com/4135215/san-bernardino-remote-bomb/ |title=San Bernardino Suspects Left Behind Failed Remote-Controlled Bomb |work=Time |date=December 3, 2015}}</ref>
The large stockpile of weapons used by Farook and Malik led investigators to believe that they intended to carry out further attacks.<ref name="HosenballBartz">{{cite news|first1=Mark|last1=Hosenball|first2=Diane|last2=Bartz|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-california-shooting-investigation-idUSKBN0TP0P920151206|title=California shooters likely planned multiple attacks&nbsp;— official|agency=Reuters|date=December 6, 2015}}</ref> An examination of digital equipment recovered from their home suggested that the couple was in the final planning stages of a much larger attack.<ref name=LATimes1>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/crime/la-me-sb-shooting-20151211-story.html|title=San Bernardino shooters planned bigger attack, investigators believe|work=Los Angeles Times|date=December 10, 2015|accessdate=December 11, 2015|first=Richard A.|last=Serrano|first2=Richard|last2=Winton|first3=Sarah|last3=Parvini|first4=James|last4=Queally}}</ref>
=== Shooting range video === After law enforcement sources confirmed that Farook spent time on November 29{{ndash}}30, 2015, at the [[Riverside, California|Riverside]] Magnum Shooting Range, about {{convert|25|mi|km}} away from the couple's Redlands home, the FBI obtained surveillance video from the range. During these visits, one lasting several hours, Farook shot an [[AR-15]] and a pistol, which he had brought to the range.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dry run: San Bernardino shooter practiced at gun range days before attack|url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2015/12/07/dry-run-san-bernardino-shooter-practiced-at-gun-range-days-before-attack/|publisher=Fox News Channel|accessdate=December 7, 2015}}</ref> One of the paper torso silhouette targets used in the video was later recovered from the couple's SUV following their deaths.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/christmas-party-triggered-san-bernardino-terror-attack-police/story?id=43884973|title=Christmas Party May Have Triggered San Bernardino Terror Attack: Police|work=ABC News|date=December 1, 2016|accessdate=December 1, 2016|first1=Megan|last1=Christie|first2=Rhonda|last2=Schwartz|first3=Josh|last3=Margolin|first4=Brian|last4=Ross}}</ref>
=== Bank transaction === Two weeks before the shooting, Farook took out a loan of {{US$|28,500}} which was deposited in his bank account. The San Francisco-based online lender [[Prosper Marketplace]] made the loan to Farook; Prosper evaluates borrowers and the loans are [[Loan origination|originated]] by a third-party bank, the Salt Lake City-based WebBank.com.<ref name="HerridgeBrowne">{{cite web|first1=Catherine|last1=Herridge|first2=Pamela|last2=Browne|title=Bank records show $28,500 deposit to Syed Farook's account two weeks before the shooting, source says|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2015/12/08/bank-records-show-28500-deposit-to-syed-farooks-account-two-weeks-before-shooting-source-says.html|publisher=Fox News Channel|date=December 8, 2015}}</ref><ref name="HosenballErman">{{cite news|first1=Mark |last1=Hosenball|first2=Michael|last2=Erman|title=FBI looking into $28,500 deposit in California shooters' account: source|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-california-shooting-account-idUSKBN0TR27P20151208|agency=Reuters|date=December 8, 2015}}</ref> On or about November 20, 2015, Farook withdrew {{US$|10,000}} in cash, and later on two {{US$|5,000}} transfers were made to what appears to be Farook's mother's bank account. Investigators were exploring the possibility that the {{US$|10,000}} was used to reimburse someone for the purchase of the rifles used in the shooting.<ref name="HerridgeBrowne" /> WebBank said that it was fully cooperating with the investigation.<ref name="WintonSerranoKroll">{{cite web|last1=Winton|first1=Richard|last2=Serrano|first2=Richard A.|last3=Knoll|first3=Corina|title=San Bernardino shooting: Attackers may have left bomb behind to kill police|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-san-bernardino-shooting-attackers-bomb-mainbar-20151208-story.html|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=December 8, 2015}}</ref>
== Terrorist attack == {{Main article|2015 San Bernardino attack}}
On the morning of the December 2 attack, Farook and Malik left their six-month-old daughter with Farook's mother at their Redlands home, telling her that they were going to a doctor's appointment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/dec/03/san-bernadino-shooting-suspects-syed-rizwan-farook-tashfeen-malik|title=San Bernardino shooting: what we know about the suspects|first=Paul|last=Lewis|work=The Guardian|date=December 3, 2015}}</ref><ref name=TurkewitzBorn /> Farook then attended a departmental event at the banquet room of the [[Inland Regional Center]].<ref name="Unfolded">{{cite news |first1=Eli |last1=Saslow |first2=Stephanie |last2=McCrummen |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/wheres-syed-how-the-san-bernardino-shooting-unfolded/2015/12/03/2ee90128-9a15-11e5-8917-653b65c809eb_story.html |title='Where's Syed?': How the San Bernardino shooting unfolded |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=December 3, 2015}}</ref><ref name="wash_Acti">{{cite web|title=Active shooter reported in San Bernardino, Calif.; authorities say multiple suspects, victims|last=Berman|first=Mark|work=The Washington Post|date=December 2, 2015|accessdate=December 2, 2015|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-nation/wp/2015/12/02/police-in-san-bernadino-calif-responding-report-of-shooting}}</ref> The event began as a semi-annual all-staff meeting and training event, and was in the process of transitioning into a department holiday party/luncheon when the shooting began.<ref name="Unfolded" /><ref name="LinWinton">{{cite news |last1=Lin II|first1=Rong-Gong|last2=Winton|first2=Richard|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-san-bernardino-suspects-sprayed-the-room-with-bullets-20151203-story.html|title=San Bernardino suspects 'sprayed the room with bullets,' police chief says|newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=December 4, 2015}}</ref>
Farook arrived at the departmental event at about 8:30{{nbsp}}am and left midway through it at around 10:30{{nbsp}}am, leaving a backpack containing explosives atop a table.<ref name=PE.Autopsy>{{cite web|url=http://www.pe.com/articles/bernardino-804074-san-county.html|title=SAN BERNARDINO SHOOTING: Autopsy reports released for Dec. 2 victims (UPDATE 2)|work=The Press-Enterprise|date=May 27, 2016|accessdate=May 29, 2016|first=Joe|last=Nelson}}</ref> Coworkers reported that Farook had been quiet for the duration of the event.<ref name="Unfolded" /><ref name="LATIMES-Americandream" /> He posed for photos with other coworkers.<ref name=gap>{{cite news|last1=Whitcomb|first1=Dan|title=Public asked to help close 18-minute gap in San Bernardino probe|url=https://news.yahoo.com/public-asked-help-close-18-minute-gap-san-230303288.html|date=January 5, 2016|accessdate=January 5, 2016|publisher=Yahoo! News|agency=Reuters}}</ref><ref name=KPCC>{{cite news|last1=KPCC Staff|title=San Bernardino shooting update: 2 suspects ID'd as Syed Farook and Tashfeen Malik|url=http://www.scpr.org/news/2015/12/02/55997/multiple-victims-reported-in-san-bernardino-shooti/|accessdate=December 3, 2015|publisher=[[KPCC]]|date=December 2, 2015}}</ref><ref name="CNNRadicalized">{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/12/03/us/san-bernardino-shooting/index.html|title=Officials: San Bernardino shooter appears radicalized|first1=Greg |last1=Botelho |first2=Kyung |last2=Lah |first3=Ben |last3=Brumfield|date=December 3, 2015|publisher=CNN}}</ref>
At 10:59{{nbsp}}am [[Pacific Standard Time|PST]], Farook and Malik armed themselves and opened fire on those in attendance.<ref name="HauserDec3" /><ref name=":1">{{cite news|title=Two Suspects Dead, Including a Woman|url=https://www.nytimes.com/live/san-bernardino-shooting/two-suspects-dead-including-a-woman|website=The New York Times|date=December 2, 2015|accessdate=December 3, 2015}}</ref><ref name="WaPoPurchase">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/suspects-in-san-bernadino-shooting-had-a-small-arsenal/2015/12/03/9b5d7b52-99db-11e5-94f0-9eeaff906ef3_story.html |title=Guns used in San Bernardino shooting were purchased legally from dealers |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=December 3, 2015}}</ref><ref name="DM">{{cite web |last=Daly |first=Michael |date=December 4, 2015 |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2015/12/04/san-bernardino-the-most-twisted-terrorist-plot-yet.html|title=San Bernardino: The Most Twisted Terrorist Plot Yet |work=The Daily Beast |accessdate=December 4, 2015}}</ref> During the attack, they wore ski masks and black tactical gear.<ref name="LinWinton" /><ref name="NPRWhatWeKnow">{{cite web |first=Camila |last=Domonoske |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2015/12/03/458277103/san-bernardino-shootings-what-we-know-one-day-after |title=San Bernardino Shootings: What We Know, One Day After |publisher=NPR |date=December 5, 2015}}</ref> The entire shooting took less than four minutes,<ref name="Unfolded" /> and Farook and Malik fired between 65 and 75 bullets. The couple departed the scene before police arrived.<ref name="DM" /> The explosive devices placed by Farook were later detonated by a [[Bomb disposal|bomb squad]].<ref name="BATFWeapons" /><ref name="APMyersPritchard">{{cite news |first1=Amanda Lee |last1=Myers |first2=Justin |last2=Pritchard |url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/2015/dec/02/california-police-respond-to-report-of-active/ |title=14 dead, 17 wounded in California shooting; 2 suspects dead |agency=Associated Press |newspaper=U-T San Diego |date=December 2, 2015}}</ref>
The attack was the second-deadliest mass shooting in California after the 1984 [[San Ysidro McDonald's massacre]]. It was also the deadliest mass shooting in the U.S. since the 2012 [[Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/san-bernardino-shooting/san-bernardino-shooting-deadliest-newtown-n473086|title=San Bernardino Shooting is Deadliest Since Newtown|first=Jon|last=Schuppe|first2=Elizabeth|last2=Chuck|first3=Helen|last3=Kwong|publisher=NBC News|date=December 2, 2015}}</ref><ref name="BBC">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-35006404 |title=San Bernardino shootings investigated as terrorism – FBI |publisher=BBC News |date=December 4, 2015 |accessdate=December 4, 2015}}</ref> and the deadliest terrorist attack to occur in the U.S. since the [[September 11 attacks]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-1227-islamic-convention-20151227-story.html|title=San Bernardino shootings cast a somber tone over Muslim conference in Chino|work=Los Angeles Times|date=December 26, 2015|accessdate=December 28, 2015|first=Cindy|last=Chang}}</ref> until both categories were surpassed by the [[2016 Orlando nightclub shooting]] six months later.<ref name="TheGuardian">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/jun/12/orlando-shooting-nightclub-pulse-gunman|title=Orlando Pulse club attack: gunman behind shooting that killed 50 'named as Omar Mateen'|last=Lyons|first=Kate|date=June 12, 2016|work=The Guardian|accessdate=June 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Lois|last=Beckett|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/jun/12/orlando-nightclub-deadliest-mass-shooting-terrorism|title=Orlando nightclub attack is deadliest US mass shooting in modern history|work=The Guardian|date=June 12, 2016|accessdate=June 12, 2016}}</ref><ref name="cnn">{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/06/12/us/orlando-nightclub-shooting/index.html|title=Police: 50 killed in Florida nightclub terror attack|first=Ashley|last=Fantz|first2=Faith|last2=Karimi|first3=Eliott C.|last3=McLaughlin|date=June 12, 2016|work=CNN|accessdate=June 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/orlando-nightclub-shooting-20-dead-terror-attack-at-florida-lgbt-club-gay-killed-explosion-bomb-a7077831.html|title=Gunman's 'terror attack' on gay nightclub leaves 50 dead|date=June 12, 2016|work=The Independent|language=en-GB|accessdate=June 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Kelly|first1=Erin|title=Trump, Clinton, congressional leaders react to Orlando shooting|url=http://www.13newsnow.com/news/nation-now/trump-clinton-congressional-leaders-react-to-orlando-shooting/240685507|accessdate=June 12, 2016|work=ABC 13 News Now|agency=USA Today|quote=House Homeland Security Chairman Michael McCaul, R-Texas, said "this appears to be the worst terrorist attack on American soil since 9/11."}}</ref> Malik was one of a small number of female mass shooters in the U.S.; women constituted only 3.75 percent of active shooters in the U.S. from 2000 to 2013.<ref>{{cite web |first=Meghan |last=Keneally |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/san-bernardino-shooting-female-shooter/story?id=35558415 |title=San Bernardino Shooter Tashfeen Malik Joins Small Group of Female Mass Murderers |publisher=ABC News |date=December 3, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Stephen |last=Smith |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/san-bernardino-shooting-female-attackers-nothing-new-abroad/ |title=A rarity in U.S., female attackers nothing new abroad |publisher=CBS News |date=December 3, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Danielle |last=Paquette |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2015/12/03/the-motives-behind-the-women-who-became-mass-shooters/ |title=Tashfeen Malik and the American women who became mass shooters |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=December 3, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.fbi.gov/news/stories/2014/september/fbi-releases-study-on-active-shooter-incidents/pdfs/a-study-of-active-shooter-incidents-in-the-u.s.-between-2000-and-2013 | title=A Study of Active Shooter Incidents in the United States Between 2000 and 2013 | publisher=FBI | date=September 16, 2013}}</ref>
=== Deaths === After the attack, a witness recognized Farook and identified him to police.<ref name="LinWinton" /><ref name="HauserDec3">{{cite news |first=Christine |last=Hauser |url=https://www.nytimes.com/live/san-bernardino-shooting/police-21-wounded-12-pipe-bombs-discovered/ |title=Police: 21 Wounded, 12 Pipe Bombs Discovered |newspaper=The New York Times |date=December 3, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = SUV in San Bernardino shooting had Utah tags, was rented in California|url = http://fox13now.com/2015/12/02/officials-at-least-20-victims-in-san-bernardino-mass-shooting/|publisher = Fox 13 |location=Salt Lake City|accessdate = December 6, 2015}}</ref> When officers responded to Farook and Malik's Redlands home, both fled in a [[sports utility vehicle]] (SUV), resulting in a police pursuit.<ref name="BATFWeapons" /><ref name="APMyersPritchard" /><ref name="ABC">{{cite web|title=14 people killed in shooting at Inland Regional Center in San Bernardino|url=http://abc7.com/news/12-killed-in-shooting-at-san-bernardino-social-services-facility/1106844|publisher=ABC7 Los Angeles|accessdate=December 3, 2015}}</ref><ref name=PE.Horror>{{cite web|url=http://www.pe.com/articles/san-804078-bernardino-officers.html|title=SAN BERNARDINO SHOOTING: Horror of Dec. 2 attack remains with rescuers|work=The Press-Enterprise|date=May 27, 2016|accessdate=May 29, 2016|first=Suzanne|last=Hurt}}</ref> At least one fake explosive was thrown at the police during the chase.<ref name="BATFWeapons" /><ref name="APMyersPritchard" />
The chase ended in a suburban neighborhood about {{convert|1.7|mi|km}} away from the scene of the initial attack. There, Farook and Malik exchanged gunfire with officers.<ref name="ABC" /> The gunfire lasted for around five minutes before both Farook and Malik were killed by police bullets.<ref name="ABC" /><ref name="Suspects"/><ref name="CNN.Hero"/> Farook died from 26 gunshot wounds, sustained mostly in the legs and including one in the chin where the bullet [[Fragmentation (weaponry)|fragmented]] into his neck. Malik died from fifteen gunshot wounds, thirteen to the body and two to the head.<ref name=CalmtoChaos/>
== Aftermath == After Farook and Malik's corpses were released by law enforcement, local [[Islamic funeral|Islamic cemeteries]] refused to accept the remains. It took a week to find a willing cemetery, and the burial ultimately took place in Rosamond, California.<ref>{{cite news|title=Enrique Marquez Charged With Conspiring With San Bernardino Shooter in 2011, 2012|url=http://ktla.com/2015/12/17/san-bernardino-mass-shooting-federal-prosecutors-expected-to-file-charges-against-gunmans-friend-enrique-marquez/|accessdate=August 19, 2016|publisher=KTLA|agency=CNN Wire|date=December 17, 2015|first1=Steve|last1=Kuzj|first2=Kirk|last2=Hawkins|first3=Rick|last3=Chambers}}</ref> According to two members of the mosque, many of the city's Muslim community refused to attend the funeral on December 15, 2015, which was attended by around ten mourners including relatives of Farook.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Abutaleb|first1=Yasmeen|title=Corrected – San Bernardino shooters buried in quiet funeral following Islamic rituals|url=http://in.reuters.com/article/california-shooting-funeral-exclusive-idINKBN0U002F20151217|accessdate=December 17, 2015|agency=Reuters|date=December 15, 2015}}</ref>
Farook and Malik's corpses were buried per traditional Muslim rituals at an Islamic cemetery, according to [[Reuters]].<ref>{{cite news|first1=Yasmeen|last1=Abutaleb|title=Exclusive: San Bernardino shooters buried in quiet funeral following Islamic rituals|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-california-shooting-funeral-idUSKBN0U002C20151217|accessdate=August 9, 2016|work=Reuters|date=December 17, 2015|quote=The funeral followed traditional Islamic rituals, said an attendee. At a Muslim cemetery hours away from San Bernardino, the bodies were cleansed according to Islamic rules.}}</ref>
In one Arabic-language online radio broadcast, ISIL described Farook and Malik as "supporters" following the attack. During the police investigation into the attack, ''The New York Times'' reported that this language indicated "a less direct connection" between the shooters and the terrorist group.<ref name=NYTimes_soldiers>{{cite news|last=Callimachi|first=Rukmini|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/06/world/middleeast/islamic-state-san-bernardino-massacre.html|title=Islamic State Says 'Soldiers of Caliphate' Attacked in San Bernardino|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 5, 2015|accessdate=December 6, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=FBI probes ISIS, terror links to San Bernardino massacre|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-san-bernardino-shooting-isis-20151204-story.html|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=December 5, 2015}}</ref> In a December 5, 2015, English-language broadcast on its [[Al-Bayan (radio station)|Bayan radio station]], ISIL referred to Farook and Malik as "soldiers of the caliphate," which is a phrase ISIL uses to denote members of the terrorist organization. ''The New York Times'' reported that it was unclear why the two versions differed.<ref name="NYTimes_soldiers" />
On February 9, 2016, the FBI announced that it was unable to unlock one of the mobile phones they had recovered from Farook and Malik's home because of the phone's advanced security features. The phone was an [[iPhone 5C]] owned by the county and issued to Farook during his employment with them.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-california-shooting-encryption-idUSKCN0VI22A|title=FBI director says investigators unable to unlock San Bernardino shooter's phone content|work=Reuters|date=February 9, 2016|accessdate=February 16, 2016|first=Dustin|last=Volz|first2=Mark|last2=Hosenball}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pe.com/articles/washington-794488-help-killer.html|title=SAN BERNARDINO SHOOTING: Apple must help US hack killer's phone|work=The Press-Enterprise|date=February 16, 2016|accessdate=February 16, 2016|first=Tami|last=Abdollah|first2=Eric|last2=Tucker}}</ref> When asked by the FBI to create a new version of the phone's [[iOS]] [[operating system]] that could be installed and run in the phone's [[random access memory]] to disable certain security features, [[Apple Inc.]] declined due to its policy to never undermine the security features of its products. The FBI responded by successfully applying to a [[United States magistrate judge]] to issue a court order under the [[All Writs Act of 1789]], mandating Apple to create and provide the requested software.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/san-bernardino-shooting/judge-forces-apple-help-unlock-san-bernardino-shooter-iphone-n519701|title=Judge Forces Apple to Help Unlock San Bernardino Shooter iPhone|work=NBC News|date=February 16, 2016|accessdate=February 16, 2016|first=Andrew|last=Blankstein}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Robert M.|last=Chesney|url=https://lawfareblog.com/apple-vs-fbi-going-dark-dispute-moves-congress-courtroom|title=Apple vs FBI: The Going Dark Dispute Moves from Congress to the Courtroom|work=Lawfare|date=February 17, 2016|accessdate=February 20, 2016}}</ref> Citing security risks posed towards their customers as a result of such software, Apple announced their intent to oppose the order, resulting in [[FBI–Apple encryption dispute|a dispute]] between the company and the FBI.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/02/16/us/san-bernardino-shooter-phone-apple/|title=Apple opposes judge's order to hack San Bernardino shooter's iPhone|work=CNN|date=February 17, 2016|accessdate=February 17, 2016|first=Evan|last=Perez|first2=Tim|last2=Hume}}</ref> The dispute eventually ended on March 28, 2016, when the [[United States Department of Justice|U.S. Department of Justice]] announced that it had unlocked the iPhone.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Technology/justice-department-withdraws-request-apple-iphone-encryption-case/story|title=Justice Department Withdraws Request in Apple iPhone Encryption Case After FBI Accesses San Bernardino Shooter's Phone|work=[[ABC News]]|first=Jack|last=Dale|first2=Mike|last2=Levine|first3=Alyssa|last3=Newcomb|date=March 28, 2016|accessdate=March 29, 2016}}</ref>
The San Bernardino County Sheriff’s Department released autopsies for the 14 victims on May 27, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pe.com/articles/bernardino-804074-san-county.html|title=SAN BERNARDINO SHOOTING: Autopsy reports released for Dec. 2 victims (UPDATE 2)|work=The Press-Enterprise|date=May 27, 2016|accessdate=March 31, 2018|first=Joe|last=Nelson}}</ref> More than two years after the attack however, autopsy reports for Farook and Malik had yet to be made public. The department responded to an April 12, 2017 Public Records Act request stating, "Currently, the autopsy reports and coroner investigations, and all other law enforcement records pertaining to the death of Syed R. Farook and Tashfeen Malik, are part of an 'investigatory file,' and are exempt from disclosure."<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Re: Public Records Act request – Autopsy Report for S. Farook & T. Malik |url= http://media.kgov.com/files/SBC-Rsp-to-KGOV-radio-re-SFarook-TMalik-Autopsies.pdf|work= AM 670 KLTT online at KGOV|location= Denver, Colorado|date= April 24, 2017|access-date= March 31, 2018}}</ref>
On May 31, 2016, federal prosecutors filed a lawsuit against Farook's family. This lawsuit would allow them to seize both the proceeds of two [[life insurance]] policies (and the policies themselves) held by Farook, both of which listed Farook's mother as the beneficiary. One policy worth {{US$|25,000}} was taken out by Farook in 2012 when he started working for the county, while the other, worth {{US$|250,000}}, was taken out the following year. According to [[NBC News]], "Under federal law, assets derived from terrorism are subject to forfeiture. A federal judge must approve an application before the government can seize the money."<ref name=SernaParviniHamiltonKnoll /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/san-bernardino-shooting/feds-file-suit-against-family-san-bernardino-shooter-seize-life-n583781|title=Feds File Suit Against Family of San Bernardino Shooter to Seize Life Insurance Policies|work=NBC News|date=June 1, 2016|accessdate=June 1, 2016|first=Andrew|last=Blankstein|first2=Elizabeth|last2=Chuck}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/feds-file-suit-to-seize-san-bernardino-shooters-life-insurance/|title=Feds file suit to seize San Bernardino shooter's life insurance|publisher=CBS News|agency=Associated Press|date=May 31, 2016|accessdate=June 1, 2016}}</ref> In the six-page lawsuit, the life insurance company claimed that Farook's mother was aware of her son's intentions to carry out the attack, and reasoned that she should not be entitled to the benefits as a result.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pe.com/articles/life-805336-farook-lawsuit.html|title=SAN BERNARDINO SHOOTING: Lawsuit reveals quandary over shooter's life insurance benefits|work=The Press-Enterprise|date=June 9, 2016|accessdate=June 12, 2016|first=Joe|last=Nelson}}</ref> On September 2, 2016, government officials said they wanted to give the money to the victims' families.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abc7.com/news/judge-may-decide-if-san-bernardino-shooters-life-insurance-money-goes-to-victims-or-mom/1496372/|title=Government Wants Money From Life Insurance Policies of San Bernardino Terror Shooter Given to Families' Victims|work=KABC-TV|date=September 2, 2016|accessdate=September 5, 2016|first=Rob|last=McMillan}}</ref>
