{{nihongo|'''Shōji Nishimura'''|西村 祥治|Nishimura Shōji|extra=30 November 1889 – 24 October 1944}} was an admiral in the [[Imperial Japanese Navy]] during [[World War II]].

==Biography==
Nishimura was from [[Akita prefecture]] in the northern [[Tōhoku region]] of Japan. He was a graduate of the 39th class of the [[Imperial Japanese Naval Academy]] in 1911, ranking 21st out of 148 cadets. As a [[midshipman]], he served on the [[cruiser]] {{Ship|Japanese cruiser|Aso||2}} and [[battleship]] {{Ship|Japanese battleship|Mikasa||2}}. After his commissioning as an [[Ensign (rank)|ensign]], he was assigned back to ''Aso'', and then to the [[battlecruiser]] {{Ship|Japanese battleship|Hiei||2}}<!-- ''Hiei'' wasn't corverted into a battleship until much later... -->.

He attended naval artillery and torpedo school from 1914–1915, and was then assigned to the [[destroyer]] {{Ship|Japanese destroyer|Yugiri|1899|2}}, cruiser {{Ship|Japanese cruiser|Yakumo||2}} and battlecruiser {{Ship|Japanese battleship|Haruna||2}}<!-- ''Haruna'' wasn't converted into a battleship until much later...-->.

As a [[lieutenant]] from 1917, he specialized in navigation, and served as chief navigator on a large number of vessels, including the [[corvette]] {{Ship|Japanese corvette|Yamato||2}}, destroyers {{Ship|Japanese destroyer|Kawakaze|1917|2}}, {{Ship|Japanese destroyer|Tanikaze|1918|2}}, {{Ship|Japanese destroyer|Yura||2}} and {{Ship|Japanese destroyer|Sunosaki||2}}, cruisers {{Ship|Japanese cruiser|Kitakami||2}} and {{Ship|Japanese cruiser|Ōi||2}}, and battleship {{Ship|Japanese battleship|Hizen||2}}. Nishimura was promoted to [[lieutenant commander]] in 1928. He was subsequently chief navigator on the cruiser {{Ship|Japanese cruiser|Nisshin||2}}. He was given his first command on 1 November 1926: the destroyer {{Ship|Japanese destroyer|Kiku|1920|2}}. He subsequently was captain of the destroyers {{Ship|Japanese destroyer|Wakatake||2}}, {{Ship|Japanese destroyer|Urakaze|1915|2}}, {{Ship|Japanese destroyer|Mikazuki|1926|2}}, and (after his promotion to [[Commander#Commander as a naval rank|commander]] in 1929) {{Ship|Japanese destroyer|Shirakumo|1927|2}}. In the 1930s, he was assigned command of the 26th Destroyer Group.

Promoted to [[Captain (naval)|captain]] in 1934, and briefly commander of the 19th Destroyer Group, Nishimura then served as captain of the cruiser {{Ship|Japanese cruiser|Kumano||2}} (from 1937–1938) and the reconstructed [[fast battleship]] ''Haruna''<!-- To differentiate between her origin as a battlecruiser and her status as a fast battleship after her moderization... --> (from 1938–1940). He became a [[rear admiral]] on 15 November 1940, and a [[Vice Admiral|vice admiral]] on 1 November 1943.

Nishimura gained much fame as the commander of the 4th Destroyer Squadron during the [[Battle of the Java Sea]]. In June 1942, he was named the commander of the 7th Cruiser Division and participated in the [[Guadalcanal Campaign]].<ref name="Klemen">{{cite web|last=Klemen|first=L|url= http://www.dutcheastindies.webs.com/nishimura.html|title=Rear-Admiral Shoji Nishimura|date= 1999–2000|work=Forgotten Campaign: The Dutch East Indies Campaign 1941-1942}}</ref>

Near the end of the war, Nishimura was named the commander of the "Southern Force"<ref name= "Klemen"/> in "Operation ''Sho-Go''", aimed at a final and decisive naval battle against the [[United States Navy]] in the [[Philippines]]. Nishimura's Force "C" consisted of battleships {{Ship|Japanese battleship|Fusō||2}} and {{Ship|Japanese battleship|Yamashiro||2}}, [[heavy cruiser]] {{Ship|Japanese cruiser|Mogami|1934|2}}, and destroyers [[Japanese destroyer Shigure (1935)|''Shigure'']], [[Japanese destroyer Michishio|''Michishio'']], [[Japanese destroyer Asagumo (1938)|''Asagumo'']], and [[Japanese destroyer Yamagumo (1937)|''Yamagumo'']]. In the [[Surigao Strait]] between [[Leyte]] and [[Dinagat Islands]] on the evening of 24 October 1944, he contacted the [[United States Seventh Fleet|U.S. 7th Fleet]] under [[Rear admiral (United States)|Rear Admiral]] [[Jesse Oldendorf]], which consisted of six battleships, eight cruisers, 29 destroyers, and 39 motor torpedo boats. Nishimura's force was crushed when the Americans [[crossing the T|crossed the Japanese "T"]]. Nishimura was killed during the battle when his flagship, the ''Yamashiro'', was sunk after being hit multiple times from the U.S. battleships.<ref name="Klemen"/>

