{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}} {{Use Australian English|date=September 2015}} {{Infobox AFL biography | name = Tommy Hughes | image = | fullname = Thomas Edward Hughes | birth_date = {{birth date|1886|12|25|df=yes}} | birth_place = At sea near [[Launceston, Tasmania]] | death_date = {{death date and age|1981|8|19|1886|12|25|df=yes}} | death_place = [[Northcote, Victoria]] | originalteam = Leopold | height = <!-- ### cm --> | weight = <!-- ### kg --> | position = Wing / Backline | statsend = 1911 | years1 = 1911 | club1 = {{AFL Car}} | games_goals1 = 6 (1) | careerhighlights = }}
'''Thomas Edward "Tommy" Hughes''' (25 December 1886 – 19 August 1981) was an [[Australian rules football]]er who played with [[Carlton Football Club|Carlton]] in the [[Australian Football League|Victorian Football League]] (VFL), usually playing on the wing or in defence.
==Military Service== He enlisted in the First AIF on 27 November 1915.
Some mistaken sources, confusing Hughes with one of two other AIF men of the same name who were killed in action,<ref>Namely, Private Thomas Edward Hughes (75) who died of his wounds on 8 October 1917, and Private Thomas Edward Hughes (4823) who was killed in action on 3 September 1916.</ref> claim that he was been killed in the Somme during [[World War I]]; when, in fact, he returned to Australia on 23 June 1919.
Other mistaken sources based their statements on the obituary of "Private Tom Hughes" that appeared in ''The Winner'' of 6 June 1917,<ref>[https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/154544661 Brave Footballers, ''The Winner'', (Wednesday, 6 June 1917), p.8.]</ref> without having seen the retraction notice published a week later,<ref>[https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/154545949 Statement Corrected, ''The Winner'', (Wednesday, 13 June 1917), p.8.]</ref> that clearly stated that the deceased "Private Tom Hughes" was not one and the same as the "Gunner Tom Hughes" who once played for Carlton.<ref>In fact, the deceased "Private Tom Hughes" was Private Albert Thomas Hughes (5985), who was killed in action on 3 May 1917 (see: [https://www.awm.gov.au/collection/R1632396 Roll of Honour: Private Albert Thomas Hughes (5985), ''Australian War Museum'']).</ref><ref>see also: Tommy Hughes, ''blueseum.org''.</ref>
==Death== He died on 19 August 1981.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=6zJVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=h5QDAAAAIBAJ&pg=1777%2C1440583 Deaths: Hughes, ''The Age'', (Thursday, 21 August 1981), p.30.]</ref>
